28","1290":"1290","Baylham, Suffolk, England":"Baylham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Barton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places called with Old English <i>bere</i> or <i>bær</i> ‘barley’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’, i.e. an outlying grange. Compare   Barwick  . The name is also found in Ireland, where it has been Gaelicized as <b>de Bartún</b>.","Polish (<b>Bartoń</b>); Czech and Slovak (mainly <b>Bartoň</b>): from a pet form of the personal name Polish <i>Bartłomiej</i>, Czech <i>Bartoloměj</i>, Slovak <i>Bartolomej</i>, from Latin <i>Bartholomaeus</i> (see   Bartholomew  ). This surname is also found in Germany."],"variants":[{"name":"Barwick","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Berwick or Barwick, for example in Northumberland, Norfolk, Somerset, and Yorkshire, from Old English <i>bere</i> ‘barley’ + <i>wīc</i> ‘outlying farm building’, i.e. a granary lying some distance away from the main settlement.","North German: habitational name from a place called Berwick, near Soest, in Westphalia."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert de Barton was born in 1295, in Baylham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom, his father, John de Barton I, was 5 and his mother, Margaret, was 25. He married Margaret Goode about 1319, in Baylham, Suffolk, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"1295–":"1295–Surnud","1295–Male":"1295–Surnud","1310–Male":"1310–Surnud","1303–Female":"1303–Surnud","1320–1344":"1320–1344","1290–1328":"1290–1328","1270–Female":"1270–Surnud","1303":"1303","about 1319":"umbes 1319","1344":"1344","1310":"1310","1320":"1320","1295":"1295","1270":"1270","1328":"1328","1290":"1290","Baylham, Suffolk, England":"Baylham, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1295–":"1295–Kuollut","1295–Male":"1295–Kuollut","1310–Male":"1310–Kuollut","1303–Female":"1303–Kuollut","1320–1344":"1320–1344","1290–1328":"1290–1328","1270–Female":"1270–Kuollut","1303":"1303","about 1319":"noin 1319","1344":"1344","1310":"1310","1320":"1320","1295":"1295","1270":"1270","1328":"1328","1290":"1290","Baylham, Suffolk, England":"Baylham, Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningas